sql:
SELECT customer_id, email, total_spent, last_purchase_date
FROM customers
WHERE total_spent > 1000 AND last_purchase_date >= DATE('now', '-1 year');

SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM customers 
WHERE income > (SELECT AVG(income) FROM customers);

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT customer_id) AS total_unique_customers
FROM customers
WHERE last_purchase_date >= date('now', '-1 year');

external_knowledge:
- "Silent vessels of wealth" metaphorically refers to customers with high income;
- "Spring and prime of life" refers to customers aged 25 to 40, representing the period of life when individuals are often in their career-building phase;
- "Still sailing" refers to customers who are active;
- "Received more than a handful of offers" means more than 5 offers;
- "Average sum they have spent on their journeys" refers to the average total spent by the customer;
- "Caught (count of offers)" metaphorically indicates the number of offers received by the customer.

- 'golden ticket' is a metaphor for the most successful offer;
- 'eager treasure hunters' refers to the customers who have successfully redeemed offers;
- 'gold pieces' metaphorically represents the amount spent by customers on the offer.

- 'exclusive offer' refers to the specific offer with a unique offer_id;
- 'money-spending groups' categorizes customers by their age;
- 'top three' refers to selecting the three highest-spending age groups based on the total spending amount.

- "bustling market of opportunities" refers to the active offers available to customers;
- "active paths are taken" means the offers must be in the 'active' status;
- "sown (spent)" refers to the amount spent by customers on offers;
- "reaped (successful offers)" means the offers where the customer successfully redeemed, indicated by the success flag 'Yes';
- "fallen short (unsuccessful offers)" means the offers where the customer did not succeed, indicated by the success flag 'No'.

